subSubSection.paragraph:
The geologic substrate in the area is sedimentary, constituted mainly of Middle-Late Eocene limestone (Karkaar limestones; 
ABBATE et al., 1994
), here and there covered (i.e., at the surface substituted) by more recent marls (Oligocene to Middle Eocene) with presence of clays, sandstones, and gypsum (e.g., the Iskushuban formation; 
ABBATE et al., 1994
). The two other known species occur both on gypsum and 

P. tuddense

may also be present on this substrate.
